Global Economic Indicators: Sectoral Contributions and Growth Analysis

Surya Vamshi Sriperambudooru

2025-08-03

1 Introduction

This project explores how the contributions of agriculture, manufacturing, and services to GDP and GNI have changed in developed and developing countries from 19702021. Using R, we apply data cleaning, exploratory analysis, visualization, correlation, and regression modeling to uncover global economic trends.

2 Data Preparation

##Impute Missing Values

# Example: Mean imputation for relevant columns
impute_cols <- c(
  "X.Agriculture..hunting..forestry..fishing..ISIC.A.B..",
  "Manufacturing..ISIC.D.",
  "X.Wholesale..retail.trade..restaurants.and.hotels..ISIC.G.H..",
  "Exports.of.goods.and.services",
  "Imports.of.goods.and.services",
  "Population",
  "Gross.National.Income.GNI..in.USD",
  "Gross.Domestic.Product..GDP."
)
for (col in impute_cols) {
  if (col %in% names(data)) {
    data[[col]][is.na(data[[col]])] <- mean(data[[col]], na.rm = TRUE)
  } else {
    message(paste("Column not found:", col))
  }
}
colSums(is.na(data))

##Sectoral Analysis

##Classify Developed vs. Developing Countries
developed_countries <- c("United States", "Canada", "United Kingdom", "Germany", "France",
                         "Italy", "Spain", "Japan", "Australia", "New Zealand",
                         "Norway", "Sweden", "Finland", "Denmark", "Switzerland",
                         "Netherlands", "Belgium", "Austria", "Ireland", "Singapore",
                         "South Korea", "Israel", "Luxembourg", "Iceland", "Portugal",
                         "Greece", "Czech Republic", "Slovenia", "Estonia", "Slovakia",
                         "Malta", "Lithuania", "Latvia", "Cyprus", "Hong Kong")
data$Country <- trimws(data$Country)
data$Development_Status <- ifelse(data$Country %in% developed_countries, "Developed", "Developing")
table(data$Development_Status)
## 
##  Developed Developing 
##       1564       8948
## Sectoral Contribution Over Time - use $ to avoid tidyverse NSE issues
data$Agriculture_Percentage <- data$X.Agriculture..hunting..forestry..fishing..ISIC.A.B.. / data$Gross.Domestic.Product..GDP. * 100
data$Manufacturing_Percentage <- data$Manufacturing..ISIC.D. / data$Gross.Domestic.Product..GDP. * 100
data$Services_Percentage <- data$X.Wholesale..retail.trade..restaurants.and.hotels..ISIC.G.H.. / data$Gross.Domestic.Product..GDP. * 100

agg_data <- data %>%
  group_by(Year, Development_Status) %>%
  summarize(
    Avg_Agriculture = mean(Agriculture_Percentage, na.rm=TRUE),
    Avg_Manufacturing = mean(Manufacturing_Percentage, na.rm=TRUE),
    Avg_Services = mean(Services_Percentage, na.rm=TRUE)
  )

# Agriculture
ggplot(agg_data, aes(x = Year, y = Avg_Agriculture, color = Development_Status)) +
  geom_line(size=1) +
  labs(title = "Agriculture Contribution Over Time", x = "Year", y = "Avg Agriculture %") +
  theme_minimal()

# Manufacturing
ggplot(agg_data, aes(x = Year, y = Avg_Manufacturing, color = Development_Status)) +
  geom_line(size=1) +
  labs(title = "Manufacturing Contribution Over Time", x = "Year", y = "Avg Manufacturing %") +
  theme_minimal()

# Services
ggplot(agg_data, aes(x = Year, y = Avg_Services, color = Development_Status)) +
  geom_line(size=1) +
  labs(title = "Services Contribution Over Time", x = "Year", y = "Avg Services %") +
  theme_minimal()

##Correlation Analysis

selected_data <- data %>%
  select(
    X.Agriculture..hunting..forestry..fishing..ISIC.A.B..,
    Manufacturing..ISIC.D.,
    X.Wholesale..retail.trade..restaurants.and.hotels..ISIC.G.H..,
    Gross.Domestic.Product..GDP.,
    Gross.National.Income.GNI..in.USD,
    Imports.of.goods.and.services,
    Exports.of.goods.and.services
  )
cor_matrix <- cor(selected_data, use = "complete.obs")
melted_cor <- melt(cor_matrix)
ggplot(melted_cor, aes(Var1, Var2, fill = value)) +
  geom_tile(color = "white") +
  scale_fill_gradient2(low="blue", high="red", mid="white", midpoint=0, limit=c(-1,1), name="Correlation") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=45, hjust=1)) +
  labs(title = "Correlation Heatmap of Economic Indicators")

##Regression Analysis

data$log_Agriculture <- log1p(data$X.Agriculture..hunting..forestry..fishing..ISIC.A.B.)
data$log_Manufacturing <- log1p(data$Manufacturing..ISIC.D.)
data$log_Services <- log1p(data$X.Wholesale..retail.trade..restaurants.and.hotels..ISIC.G.H..)
data$NetExports <- data$Exports.of.goods.and.services - data$Imports.of.goods.and.services

reg_model <- lm(
  log1p(Gross.National.Income.GNI..in.USD) ~ log_Agriculture + log_Manufacturing +
    log_Services + NetExports + Population,
  data = data
)
summary(reg_model)

##Conclusion

Services have become the main driver of growth in developed nations.

Manufacturing and agriculture are still key for developing countries but declining as economies mature.

Sectoral transitions are strongly correlated with GDP/GNI growth, especially after key income thresholds.

Effective policy requires promoting sectoral balance for sustainable, equitable growth.
